			<h1 align="center">Attributes</h1>
			<hr>
			<div class="background">
				<h2>What are attributes?</h2>
			</div>
			<p><strong>Attributes</strong> provide additional information about an element. They are special words used inside the <b><i>start tag</i></b> to control the element's behaviour. An <strong>attribute</strong> either modifies the default functionality of an element type or provides functionality to certain element types unable to function correctly without them.</p>
			 <div class="note">
				 <p><strong>Remember:</strong> All <strong>HTML</strong> elements can have attributes.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="background">
				<h2>Basic Attribute Types</h2>
			</div>
			<div class="example">
				<ul style="list-style-type:square">
					<li><strong>Required Attributes</strong> - Needed by a particular element type for that element type to function correctly.</li>
					<li><strong>Optional Attributes</strong> - Used to modify the default functionality of an element type.</li>
					<li><strong>Standard Attributes</strong> - Supported by a large number of element types.</li>
					<li><strong>Event Attributes</strong> - Used to cause element types to specify scripts to be run under specific circumstances.</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
			<div class="background">
				<h2>Syntax</h2>
			</div>
			<p><strong>Attributes</strong> usually come in name/value pairs, such as <b>name="value"</b>.</p>
			<p>The <b>name</b> is the property you want to set and <b>"value"</b> is what you want the value of the property to be set and always put within double quotes.</p>
			<div class="example">
				<p><strong>Example:</strong> &lt;a href=&quot;planet.html&quot;&gt; <b>or</b> &lt;h1 align="center"&gt;</p>
			</div>
			<div class="background">
				<h2>Global Attributes</h2>
			</div>
			<p>The following global attributes can be used on <strong>any</strong> HTML element:</p>
			<ul style="list-style-type:square">
				<li><b>acceskey</b></li>
				<li><b>class</b></li>
				<li><b>contenteditable</b></li>
				<li><b>data-*</b></li>
				<li><b>dir</b></li>
				<li><b>draggable</b></li>
				<li><b>dropzone</b></li>
				<li><b>hidden</b></li>
				<li><b>id</b></li>
				<li><b>lang</b></li>
				<li><b>spellcheck</b></li>
				<li><b>style</b></li>
				<li><b>tabindex</b></li>
				<li><b>title</b></li>
				<li><b>translate</b></li>
			</ul>
			<p>&#10145; If you would like to know more about each global attribute mentioned above click <a href="https://www.w3schools.com/tags/ref_standardattributes.asp">here</a>.</p>
			<div class="background">
				<h2>Useful HTML attributes</h2>
			</div>
			<h3>HTML href Attribute</h3>
			<p>For &lt;a&gt; and &lt;area&gt; elements, the href attribute specifies the URL of the page the link goes to.</p>
			<p>For &lt;base&gt; elements, the href attribute specifies the base URL for all relative URLs on a page.</p>
			<p>For &lt;link&gt; elements, the href attribute specifies the location (URL) of the external resource.</p>
			<div class="example">
				<p><strong>&lt;a&gt; Example:</strong> the <strong>href</strong> attribute specifies where the link is going to take you.</p>
				<p>&lt;a href=&quot;your destination URL goes here&quot;&gt;</p>
				<p><strong>&lt;area&gt; Example:</strong> a map of images where you can click on areas.</p>
				<p>&lt;area shape=&quot;desiredShape&quot; coords=&quot;X,Y,Z,W&quot; href=&quot;image.htm&quot; alt=&quot;Image&quot;&gt;</p>
				<p><strong>&lt;base&gt; Example:</strong> specify a base URL for all relative URLs on a particular page.</p>
				<p>&lt;base href=&quot;your specific URL goes here&quot;&gt;</p>
				<p><strong>&lt;link&gt; Example:</strong> link straight to your choice of external stylesheet.</p>
				<p>&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheetwhatever&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;whatevertheme.css&quot;&gt;</p>
			</div>
			<p>Browsers that support the <strong>href</strong> attribute: Chrome, Internet Explorer, Firefox, Safari, and Opera.</p>
			<h3>HTML src Attribute</h3>
			<p>The <strong>src</strong> attribute instructs the browser where on the server it should look for the object thatâ€™s to be presented to the user. This may be an object in the same directory, an oject somewhere else on the same server, or even an object stored on another server.</p>
			<h4>Elements which applies to:</h4>
			<ul style="list-style-type:square">
				<li>&lt;audio&gt;</li>
				<li>&lt;embed&gt;</li>
				<li>&lt;iframe&gt;</li>
				<li>&lt;img&gt;</li>
				<li>&lt;input&gt;</li>
				<li>&lt;script&gt;</li>
				<li>&lt;source&gt;</li>
				<li>&lt;track&gt;</li>
				<li>&lt;video&gt;</li>
			</ul>
			<p><strong>Let's take a look at some syntax examples for the following events:</strong></p>
			<div class="example">
				<p><strong>&lt;embed&gt; Example:</strong> an embedded flash animation.</p>
				<p>&lt;embed src=&quot;whateveryouwant.swf&quot;&gt;</p>
				<p><strong>&lt;img&gt; Example:</strong> image of your choice which is marked up.</p>
				<p>&lt;img src=&quot;helloworld.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Hello World&quot;&gt;</p>
				<p><strong>&lt;script&gt; Example:</strong> point to an external JavaScript file.</p>
				<p>&lt;script src=&quot;yourscript.js&quot;&gt;</p>
				<p><strong>&lt;source&gt; Example:</strong> assume there is an mp3 player with two source files. The browser has to choose which file it has support for. Neither is still an option.</p>
				<p>&lt;audio controls&gt;<br> &nbsp; &lt;source src=&quot;hello.ogg&quot; type=&quot;audio/ogg&quot;&gt;<br> &nbsp; &lt;source src=&quot;world.mp3&quot; type=&quot;audio/mpeg&quot;&gt;<br> Your browser does not support the audio element.<br> &lt;/audio&gt;</p>
			</div>
			<p>Browsers that support the <strong>src</strong> attribute include: Chrome, Internet Explorer, Firefox, Safari, and Opera.<strong> For this attribute, it is important to check the browser version before using it</strong>.</p>
			<h3>HTML width Attribute</h3>
			<p>The <strong>width</strong> attribute specifies the width of the element, in pixels.</p>
			<div class="example">
				<p><strong>&lt;embed&gt; Example:</strong> an embedded flash animation with a width and height of 100 pixels.</p>
				<p>&lt;embed src=&quot;youranimation.swf&quot; width=&quot;100&quot; height=&quot;100&quot;&gt;</p>
				<p><strong>&lt;img&gt; Example:</strong> image of your choice which is marked up with a width and height of 100 pixels.</p>
				<p>&lt;img src=&quot;helloworld.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Hello World&quot; width=&quot;100&quot; height=&quot;100&quot;&gt;</p>
				<p><strong>&lt;iframe&gt; Example:</strong> an &lt;iframe&gt; element with a specified width and height of 100 pixels.</p>
				<p>&lt;iframe src=&quot;/default.asp&quot; width=&quot;100&quot; height=&quot;100&quot;&gt;</p>
			</div>
			<p>Browsers that support the <strong>width</strong> attribute include: Chrome, Internet Explorer, Firefox, Safari, and Opera.<strong> For this attribute, it is important to check the browser version before using it</strong>.</p>
			<h3>HTML height Attribute</h3>
			<p>The <strong>height</strong> attribute specifies the height of the element, in pixels.</p>
			<p>In the followig examples, we used 100 pixels for the width and 200 pixels for the height.</p>
			<div class="example">
				<p><strong>&lt;img&gt; Example:</strong> &lt;img src=&quot;yourimage.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Your Image&quot; width=&quot;100&quot; height=&quot;200&quot;&gt;</p>
				<p><strong>&lt;object&gt; Example:</strong> &lt;object data=&quot;youranimation.swf&quot; width=&quot;100&quot; height=&quot;200&quot;&gt;</p>
				<p><strong>&lt;embed&gt; Example:</strong> &lt;embed src=&quot;youranimation.swf&quot; width=&quot;100&quot; height=&quot;200&quot;&gt;</p>
			</div>
			<p>Browsers that support the <strong>height</strong> attribute include: Chrome, Internet Explorer, Firefox, Safari, and Opera.<strong> For this attribute, it is important to check the browser version before using it</strong>.</p>
			<h3>HTML alt Attribute</h3>
			<p>The <strong>alt</strong> attribute provides alternative information for an image if a user for some reason cannot view it. Those reasons include: slow connection, an error in the src attribute, or users using a screen reader.</p>
			<div class="note">
				<p><strong>Remember:</strong> the <strong>alt</strong> attribute is required for the <strong>&lt;img&gt;</strong> element and for  and for <strong>&lt;input&gt;</strong> elements, the <strong>alt</strong> attribute can only be used with <strong>&lt;input type=&quot;image&quot;&gt;</strong>.</p>
			</div>
			<p>Browsers that support the <strong>alt</strong> attribute include: Chrome, Internet Explorer, Firefox, Safari, and Opera.</p>
			<h3>HTML lang Attribute</h3>
			<p>The <strong>lang</strong> attribute is used to identify the language of text content on the web. The most common <strong>lang</strong> attributes are &quot;en&quot; for English, &quot;es&quot; for Spanish, and &quot;fr&quot; for France. Since the <strong>lang</strong> attribute does not make an apparent difference, it is usually forgotten.</p>
			<p>The <strong>lang</strong> attribute is part of the <strong>Global Attributes</strong>, and therefore, can be used on <strong>any</strong> HTML element you wish.</p>
			<div class="example">
				<p><strong>&lt;html&gt; Example:</strong> &lt;html lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;</p>
				<p><strong>&lt;p&gt; Example:</strong> &lt;p lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;Some text in English.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
			</div>
			<p>Browsers that support the <strong>lang</strong> attribute include: Chrome, Internet Explorer, Firefox, Safari, and Opera.</p>
			<h3>HTML title Attribute</h3>
			<p>The <strong>title</strong> attribute specifies extra information about an element. It is usually used to provide additional information about a link or an image.</p>
			<p>Since the <strong>title</strong> attribute is part of the <strong>Global Attributes</strong>, it can be used on <strong>any</strong> HTML element you wish.</p>
			<p>A common example of the usage of the HTML <strong>title</strong> attribute would be the following:</p>
			<div class="example">
				<p><strong>Example:</strong> &lt;p title=&quot;Technology Task 1: Foundation&quot;&gt;web.cse.ohio-state.edu&lt;/p&gt;</p>
			</div>
			<p>Browsers that support the <strong>title</strong> attribute include: Chrome, Internet Explorer, Firefox, Safari, and Opera.</p>
			<h3>HTML style Attribute</h3>
			<p>The <strong>style</strong> attribute specifies the style for a particular element of your choice. Since it has &lt;higher&gt; priority, it will override any style set globally, such as styles specified in the <b><i>&lt;style&gt;</i></b> tag or in a possible external style sheet.</p>
			<p>&#10145; You can find out more about style attributes in the <a href="goes to CSS section">CSS section</a>.</p>
